## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Breaking Changes

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The modern replacement is `CancellationToken` with `Task`-based async.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner stack traces
            System.Runtime.ExceptionServices.ExceptionDispatchInfo
                .Capture(ex.InnerException!)
                .Throw();
            throw; // unreachable, satisfies compiler
        }
    }

    // Async overload (preferred)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cooperative cancellation** | Unlike `Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative* — the `work` delegate **must** check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to I/O APIs. Unchecked CPU-bound loops will ignore the timeout. |
| **`Task.Run` vs `Thread`** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. Long-running work can starve the pool. Use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)` if needed. |
| **`GetAwaiter().GetResult()`** | Blocks the caller like the original `thread.Join()`, but can deadlock on UI/ASP.NET sync contexts. Prefer the async overload. |
| **Fire-and-forget on timeout** | `Thread.Abort()` forcibly stopped work. With cancellation, uncooperative work **keeps running** after timeout. For true hard-kill, isolate in a child `Process`. |
| **`default(T)` capture** | The original code captured `result` on a closure across threads with no memory barrier. `Task.Run` handles marshaling correctly. |

### Caller Migration Example

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var data = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — sync
var data = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // pass token into the call
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — async (preferred)
var data = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

The fundamental shift: **you can no longer kill work externally**. Every cancellable operation must accept and respect a `CancellationToken`.
